<ArticleId IdType="pubmed">38472477</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>DeTora LM, Toroser D, Sykes A, et al. Good Publication Practice (GPP) guidelines for company-sponsored biomedical research: 2022 update. Ann Intern Med. 2022;175(9):1298&#x2013;1304.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">36037471</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41473436</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>31</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>02</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-eCollection"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">2234-943X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>15</Volume><PubDate><Year>2025</Year></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Frontiers in oncology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Front Oncol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Avapritinib in the treatment of systemic mastocytosis with associated acute myeloid leukemia after poor graft function following allogeneic hematopoietic stem cell transplantation: a case study and review of the literature.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1728830</StartPage><MedlinePgn>1728830</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">1728830</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.3389/fonc.2025.1728830</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="INTRODUCTION" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">This case is reported due to its novelty in demonstrating the efficacy of avapritinib, a selective <i>KIT</i> inhibitor, in a rare systemic mastocytosis-associated acute myeloid leukemia (SM-AML) patient with non-D816V <i>KIT</i> mutations and <i>RUNX1::RUNX1T1</i> fusion. Avapritinib is established for <i>KIT</i> D816V-mutant advanced systemic mastocytosis (AdvSM). However, its role in non-D816V <i>KIT</i> mutant SM-AHN post-allogeneic hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (Allo-HSCT) remains unexplored, highlighting the need to document this therapeutic challenge and outcome.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CASE PRESENTATION" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">A 15-year-old Asian male with SM-AML underwent induction chemotherapy, targeted therapy, and Allo-HSCT, but experienced graft failure with persistent mastocytosis. Post-Allo-HSCT avapritinib was initiated due to high proportion of mast cells (MCs). After 14 months, the patient achieved minimal residual disease (MRD)-negative complete remission, full donor chimerism (100%), and sustained hematologic recovery without adverse events. MC burden declined from 14.06% to 0.3%, and <i>RUNX1::RUNX1T1</i> fusion became undetectable.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">This case highlights avapritinib's potential as a salvage therapy for non-D816V <i>KIT</i> mutant SM-AML post-Allo-HSCT, effectively reducing MC clones and restoring donor chimerism. It suggests that avapritinib may bridge therapeutic gaps for atypical <i>KIT</i>-mutant systemic mastocytosis with associated hematologic neoplasm (SM-AHN) that is ineligible for Allo-HSCT or relapsed. Prospective trials are warranted to validate its efficacy, optimize dosing, and explore synergies with Allo-HSCT, offering new strategies for these high-risk patients.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Mi, Li, Chen, Wang, Ma, Fu and Wei.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y" EqualContrib="Y"><LastName>Mi</LastName><ForeName>Ruihua</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The Affiliated Cancer Hospital of Zhengzhou University &amp; Henan Cancer Hospital, Zhengzhou,&#xa0;China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y" EqualContrib="Y"><LastName>Li</LastName><ForeName>Xiang</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The Affiliated Cancer Hospital of Zhengzhou University &amp; Henan Cancer Hospital, Zhe